        "## 5. Why ML beats a fixed rule here\n",
        "\n",
        "*What makes the pattern too messy for an if-statement?*"
      ],
      "id": "AIlkA2RNfm8W"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The dataset is too messy for an if-statement because each page's performance depends on many factors such as engagement rate, AI citations and search visibility. Creating a single if-statement that uses all of these factors will be unrealistic and difficult, while machine learning will be able to identify patterns and trends across each variable in the dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "Also, because each page will be made with a different context, a different audience and different performance standards, I will not be able to create a fixed rule that correctly identifies if a page is in decline, how severe the decline is and how the page should be ranked compared to the other pages. Using Machine Learning means that the relative performance of each page can be taken into account, and compared to the relative performance of other pages to determine the order they should be ranked in."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uhSC4qusP4DG"
